<br>
That aside, I support the war on Iraq. Now I know you're thinking, &quot;omg wtf trait0rz n00vb&quot; but hold on. About 3 or so months ago, when this whole war on Iraq thing began, I was completely anti-war. I saw no point in it. Now as time passed, Saddam showed he does not wish to <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>unconditionally</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> comply with weapons inspectors from the U.N. I believe it was 10 years ago when we first offered Saddam a chance.<br>
<br>
Now, after all of his, &quot;No, you can't look there . . . strategic, uhh, map drawing room.&quot; tactics people still wish to give him more time. Bottom line, Saddam has got to go. It's obvious he will put up a fight. He said he'd rather die than go into exile, then so be it.<br>
<br>
They've already attacked U.S. aircraft patrolling the no-fly zone of southern Iraq. We retaliated. They've done several other pittiful attacks to seemingly provoke us.<br>
<br>
Saddam has attacked our allies, he's attacked innocent people, he's tortured prisoners, he intimidates his own citizens, he's threatened attacks on the U.S. and other countries, etc. We can list the bad, we can list the good, but it's obvious what comes out on top.<br>
<br>
Oh, and lastly, these human shields. Gee, that's a smart idea. Protest by blocking bullets. I'd love to nail one of these morons myself. If you want to protest, combat our war efforts. Don't just stand with a sign expecting the troops to say, &quot;Oh, they've got signs. We're screwed.&quot;<br>
<br>
Several of these human shield hopped a plane back to the U.S. saying they found the occupation to be a &quot;health risk.&quot; When you say something like that, its obvious you desirve whats coming to you.<br>
